# Prisma Conventions

## Schema

- Single schema file at `apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma`.
- Every model has `id` (UUID, `@default(uuid())`), `createdAt`, `updatedAt`.
- Every model has `workspaceId` FK (for v2 multi-tenancy). v1 uses single default workspace.
- Soft delete via `deletedAt DateTime?` — never hard-delete user data.

```prisma
model Agent {
  id          String      @id @default(uuid())
  workspaceId String
  workspace   Workspace   @relation(fields: [workspaceId], references: [id])
  name        String
  status      AgentStatus @default(DRAFT)
  createdAt   DateTime    @default(now())
  updatedAt   DateTime    @updatedAt
  deletedAt   DateTime?
}

enum AgentStatus {
  DRAFT
  PUBLISHED
  ARCHIVED
}
```

## Naming

- Models: `PascalCase` singular (`User`, `Agent`, `Conversation`).
- Fields: `camelCase`.
- Enums: `PascalCase` with `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` values.
- Relations: named explicitly to avoid ambiguity.

## Migrations

- Always use `prisma migrate dev` for development, `prisma migrate deploy` for production.
- Never use `db push` or `synchronize: true` in production.
- Migration names should be descriptive: `add-agent-status-field`, not `migration-1`.

## Agent Migration Policy

**Never run `prisma migrate dev` or `prisma generate` automatically.**

When a schema change is needed:
1. Update `apps/api/prisma/schema.prisma` only.
2. Tell the user what changed and show the suggested migration command.
3. Stop — do not execute the migration.

Only run migration or generation commands when the user explicitly says so (e.g. "run the migration", "generate", "apply it").

## Security

- API keys and secrets: encrypt before storing (AES-256). Never store plaintext.
- Password hashes: argon2. The `passwordHash` field is never selected in queries by default.
- Use `@db.Text` for large fields (system prompts, message content).
